===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[criticize]] severely.
#* ''Matthew 11:20'',
#*: Then began he to '''upbraid''' the cities wherein most of his mighty works were done.
#* [[w:Philip Sidney|Sir Philip Sidney]] {{rfdate}},
#*: How much doth thy kindness '''upbraid''' my wickedness!
# {{context|transitive|archaic|lang=en}} To charge with something wrong or disgraceful; to [[reproach]]; to cast something in the teeth of; – followed by ''with'' or ''for'', and formerly ''of'', before the thing imputed.
#* ''Mark 16:14'',
#*: And '''upbraided''' them with their unbelief.
#* Shakespeare
#*: Yet do not '''upbraid''' us our distress.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} To treat with [[contempt]].
#: {{rfquotek|Spenser}}
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} To object or urge as a matter of [[reproach]]; to cast up; – with ''to'' before the person.
#: {{rfquotek|Francis Bacon}}
# {{context|archaic|intransitive|lang=en}} To utter upbraidings.
# {{context|UK|_|dialectal|Northern England|lang=en}} To rise on the stomach; [[vomit]]; [[retch]].

